  "reading": [
    {
      "id": "gym-r1-ai-ethics",
      "title": "Artificial Intelligence: Promise and Peril",
      "description": "En analytisk text om AI:s möjligheter och etiska utmaningar.",
      "icon": "🤖",
      "pointsRequired": 0,
      "bonusPoints": 40,
      "text": "The rapid advancement of artificial intelligence represents perhaps the most significant technological shift since the Industrial Revolution. From diagnosing cancer more accurately than oncologists to generating fluent text and realistic images, AI systems are reshaping what machines can do. Yet this transformation brings with it profound ethical, social, and philosophical questions that society has barely begun to grapple with.\n\nProponents of AI development argue that the technology holds enormous potential for human flourishing. Machine learning algorithms can identify patterns in medical data that would take human doctors years to detect, potentially saving millions of lives. In climate science, AI models can process vast quantities of environmental data, improving our ability to predict and respond to extreme weather events. Economically, automation is projected to create new categories of employment even as it displaces others — a pattern observed during every previous technological revolution.\n\nCritics, however, point to a range of serious concerns. The opacity of many AI systems — often described as 'black boxes' — makes it difficult to understand how decisions are made, raising accountability issues when those decisions affect employment, credit, or criminal justice. Algorithmic bias, where AI systems perpetuate or amplify existing social inequalities, has been documented in contexts ranging from facial recognition to hiring software.\n\nNavigating these questions requires interdisciplinary collaboration — technologists, ethicists, policymakers, and the public must engage together. The choices made in the next decade will shape the trajectory of this technology for generations to come.",
      "author": "Adapted from a contemporary technology essay",
      "questions": [
        {
          "id": "gym-r1-q1",
          "type": "on-the-line",
          "question": "What term does the author use to describe AI systems whose decision-making is not transparent?",
          "options": [
            "Dark systems",
            "Black boxes",
            "Hidden networks",
            "Closed circuits"
          ],
          "correctIndex": 1,
          "explanation": "The text refers to AI systems as 'black boxes' — a term used when the internal workings are not visible or understandable."
        },
        {
          "id": "gym-r1-q2",
          "type": "between-the-lines",
          "question": "What does the author imply by comparing AI to 'every previous technological revolution' in the context of employment?",
          "options": [
            "That AI will destroy all jobs permanently.",
            "That technological change typically both eliminates some jobs and creates new ones.",
            "That previous revolutions had no impact on employment.",
            "That AI is less disruptive than previous technologies."
          ],
          "correctIndex": 1,
          "explanation": "The author says AI will 'create new categories of employment even as it displaces others — a pattern observed during every previous technological revolution', implying this is a recurring historical process."
        },
        {
          "id": "gym-r1-q3",
          "type": "beyond-the-lines",
