      "pointsRequired": 0,
      "bonusPoints": 40,
      "text": "The morning briefing arrived at precisely 07:00, as it always did. Mira had long since stopped reading it in full. The language was the same — reassuring, measured, deliberately bland — and the message never varied: the situation was improving, the Protocol was working, patience was required.\n\nShe ate her breakfast standing at the window. Below, the street was almost empty. The few people who moved along the pavement did so quickly, heads angled downward, the particular gait of those who had learned that eye contact was an invitation to misunderstanding. Mira remembered — was it five years ago, six? — when this street had been full of voices, when arguments had spilled out from café tables onto the cobblestones.\n\nThe notification chimed. A flag had been placed on yesterday's search history. 'Climate of Solidarity, 1989' — a book, nothing more. She had been curious about a historical reference in an article. Now, presumably, she would need to explain herself.\n\nMira set down her coffee cup with the careful deliberateness she had cultivated over the past few years. She was not afraid, she told herself. Fear was useful only when there was still something to protect.\n\nShe thought of her daughter, asleep in the next room. Then she opened the reply window and began to type.",
